<DOC><DOCNO> AP880407-0150 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 1417EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-India-US     04-07 0205</FIRST><SECOND>AM-India-US,0211</SECOND><HEAD>U.S. to Sell Gyroscopes to India</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The United States has agreed to sellIndia a ring laser gyroscope for use in India's development of itsown light combat aircraft.   The sale of the device, which is used to stabilize the steeringmechanism of a jet, is the latest in a series of technologytransfers from the Untied States to India for the project. Lastyear, the United States approved the transfer of 10 GeneralElectric engines for the plane.   The sale of the gyroscope was announced Wednesday by U.S.Defense Secretary Frank C. Carclucci, who noted that ``since thememorandum of understanding in 1983, the transfer of technologyitems has gone up by 400 percent'' from the United States to India.   The agreement was signed by Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's motherand predecessor, Indira Gandhi.   Talks on further transfer of technology for the combat aircraftare continuing.   Carlucci also confirmed that ``there has been formalnotification to Congress'' of the transfer of 11 F-16 fighter jetsto Pakistan. He described them as ``attrition aircraft'' to replacejets Pakistan had lost.   He said the jets were part of the recently approved $1.04billion, six-year aid package to Pakistan.</TEXT></DOC>